  "prompt": "Besides platinum+rhodium for NOx reduction and platinum+palladium for CO reduction, which catalyst can be used in catalytic converters?",
  "response": "In addition to platinum-rhodium and platinum-palladium, other catalysts that can be used in catalytic converters include:\n\n1. **Copper-Zeolite Catalysts**: These are often used in selective catalytic reduction (SCR) systems for reducing nitrogen oxides (NOx). Copper-zinc oxide catalysts can also be utilized, especially in conjunction with other materials.\n\n2. **Palladium-Copper**: This combination can be effective for oxidation reactions, particularly for hydrocarbons and CO, and may be seen in some catalytic converter designs.\n\n3. **Nickel Catalysts**: Sometimes used for hydrogenation reactions or in specific applications, though less common than the noble metal combinations.\n\n4. **Rhodium-Palladium**: This combination may also be utilized for certain specific reactions associated with emissions control.\n\n5. **Cerium Oxide**: While not a catalyst in the traditional sense, cerium oxide can serve as an oxygen storage component, improving the efficiency of catalytic processes by buffering oxygen availability.\n\nEach of these catalysts has unique properties and may be used depending on the specific requirements of the emissions control system and the fuel type. Advances in catalytic materials and research are continually exploring new catalysts, including more earth-abundant and less expensive alternatives.",
